    "Paleo %@" : {
      "comment" : "A label that reads \"Paleo ת\"",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "Paleo-Hebrew" : {
      "comment" : "Title of a feature that converts between modern square script and ancient Paleo-Hebrew with archaeological cleaning.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "Paleo-Hebrew (also called Old Hebrew script) is the original script used to write Hebrew from approximately the 10th century BCE. It is closely related to the Phoenician alphabet and is the ancestor of many modern scripts including Greek, Latin, and Arabic. Each of the 22 Paleo-Hebrew letters maps directly to its modern square Hebrew equivalent." : {
      "comment" : "Description of the Paleo-Hebrew script, including its origins and relationship to modern scripts.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "Paleo-Hebrew characters are encoded in the Phoenician Unicode block (U+10900–U+1091F). Not all devices render these characters; the grid above uses the modern equivalents for reliable display." : {
      "comment" : "A description of the Paleo-Hebrew alphabet chart.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "Paleo-Hebrew experienced a deliberate revival on Jewish coinage as a national symbol:\n\n• Hasmonean coins (2nd–1st century BCE) — The Maccabees minted coins with Paleo-Hebrew legends like “Yehonatan the King” and “Yehudah the High Priest,” asserting continuity with ancient Israelite sovereignty.\n\n• Bar Kokhba revolt coins (132–136 CE) — Simon bar Kokhba’s rebels overstruck Roman coins with Paleo-Hebrew inscriptions reading “For the Freedom of Jerusalem” and “Year One of the Redemption of Israel.” These are among the last widespread uses of the script." : {
      "comment" : "List of coins minted during the Hasmonean and Bar Kokhba revolts.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "Paleo-Hebrew is encoded in the Phoenician block of Unicode (U+10900–U+1091F). These are Supplementary Multilingual Plane characters, so font and rendering support varies across devices. AlephTools handles the mapping internally for reliable conversion." : {
      "comment" : "Description of the Paleo-Hebrew script, including its Unicode block and how it is represented in AlephTools.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
