    "Text" : {

    },
    "Text Reversal (RTL Fix)" : {
      "comment" : "Title of a learning topic that covers the issue of Hebrew text appearing in non-RTL software.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The “Strip Niqqud” tool removes all these diacritical marks, converting fully vocalized text into the standard unpointed form used in everyday writing." : {
      "comment" : "Text describing the functionality of the Strip Niqqud tool, which converts Hebrew text into its standard unpointed form.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The ancient letterforms of Israel" : {
      "comment" : "Subtitle for the Paleo-Hebrew script topic.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The first 9 letters represent 1–9, the next 9 represent 10–90, and the final 4 represent 100–400. Final letter forms (sofit) typically carry the same value as their non-final counterparts." : {
      "comment" : "Text describing the value of the final letters in the Hebrew number system.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The Hebrew Alphabet" : {
      "comment" : "Title of a screen that shows the Hebrew alphabet.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The Hebrew alphabet (aleph-bet) consists of 22 consonant letters. It is an abjad — a writing system where vowels are typically omitted or indicated with optional diacritical marks called niqqud." : {
      "comment" : "The description of the Hebrew alphabet, including its 22 consonant letters, its abjad nature, and the optional diacritical marks called niqqud.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The modern Hebrew letterforms are formally known as Ktav Ashuri (“Assyrian script”). After the Babylonian exile in the 6th century BCE, Jewish scribes gradually adopted the Aramaic square letterforms in place of the older Paleo-Hebrew script. By the Second Temple period, square script had become the standard for everyday writing." : {
      "comment" : "Hebrew letterforms used in modern Hebrew writing.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The name comes from the blocky, rectangular shape of the letters. Unlike Paleo-Hebrew’s angular, pictographic forms, square script has consistent vertical and horizontal strokes that sit neatly on a baseline. This regularity made it well-suited for scribal copying." : {
      "comment" : "Explanation of why the Hebrew script is called \"square.\"",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The Number System" : {
      "comment" : "Title of a section in the Hebrew calculator widget.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The numerical value of Hebrew words" : {
      "comment" : "Subtitle for the gematria learning topic.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The problem, visualized" : {
      "comment" : "A heading for the problem of RTL support in SwiftUI.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The RTL problem appears across many categories:\n\n• Game engines — Unity (legacy UI), older Godot, RPG Maker, GameMaker\n• 3D software — Cinema 4D text objects, Blender (pre-3.1), 3ds Max\n• Subtitles — SRT files have no directionality metadata; some players render Hebrew reversed\n• LED signage — Many sign controllers are LTR-only\n• Laser/CNC engraving — Label printers and engravers often lack BiDi" : {
      "comment" : "List of software that doesn't support Hebrew text directionality.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The SI 1452 Hebrew keyboard layout is the standard used in Israel. Each QWERTY key maps to a specific Hebrew letter." : {
      "comment" : "A description of the Hebrew keyboard layout.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The Siloam Inscription" : {
      "comment" : "Title of a learning topic that describes the Siloam Inscription, a 1st-century BCE Hebrew inscription found in Jerusalem.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The standard Hebrew keyboard layout maps each key on a QWERTY keyboard to a Hebrew letter. When someone types in English while their keyboard is set to Hebrew (or vice versa), the result is gibberish that maps letter-for-letter to the other layout." : {
      "comment" : "Text describing the standard Hebrew keyboard layout.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "The Tel Dan Stele" : {

    },
    "This happens frequently to bilingual typists. You start typing a URL or password and realize your keyboard was set to the wrong language. The “To Hebrew” and “To English” tools reverse this mapping, recovering the intended text without retyping." : {
      "comment" : "A description of a common problem related to Hebrew keyboard layouts.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "To add a Hebrew keyboard on macOS:\n\n1. Open System Settings\n2. Go to Keyboard › Input Sources\n3. Click the + button\n4. Search for and add Hebrew\n\nUse the input menu in the menu bar (or press Control+Space) to switch layouts. With the Hebrew layout active, each key press shows the Hebrew mapping — try the interactive widget above to preview it." : {
      "comment" : "Text describing how to add a Hebrew keyboard on macOS.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
